context: <b0_0>Old English<b0_0/> was first written in runes, using the futhorc – a rune set derived from the Germanic 24-character elder futhark, extended by <b1_0>five<b1_0/> more runes used to represent Anglo-Saxon vowel sounds, and sometimes by several more additional characters. From around the 9th century, the runic system came to be supplanted by a (minuscule) <b2_0>half-uncial script<b2_0/> of the Latin alphabet introduced by <b3_0>Irish Christian missionaries.<b3_0/> This was replaced by insular script, a cursive and pointed version of the half-uncial script. This was used until the end of the 12th century when continental <b4_0>Carolingian minuscule<b4_0/> (also known as Caroline) replaced the insular.
